  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent, detect, and report money laundering activities. These typically include:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence (CDD)\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Conducting background checks\n- Monitoring suspicious transactions\n- Maintaining detailed records\n\n2. Reporting Requirements\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Reporting large cash transactions\n- Notifying authorities about potential money laundering activities\n\n3. Compliance Regulations\n- Following Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) guidelines\n- Implementing Anti-Money Laundering (AML) programs\n- Conducting regular risk assessments\n\n4. Training\n- Educating staff about money laundering risks\n- Providing ongoing compliance training\n- Developing internal detection protocols\n\n5. Transaction Monitoring\n- Using automated systems to flag unusual activities\n- Tracking high-risk transactions\n- Investigating potential money laundering indicators\n\nFailure to comply with these obligations can result in significant legal penalties, including substantial fines and potential criminal charges for institutional leadership.\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any of these specific aspects of money laundering prevention?",
